k at a few more things:\n\n1. The eventbus consumer has a potential issue: `Star
t` waits for all goroutines via `wg.Wait()` but `Stop` also calls `wg.Wait()`. T
his could cause issues if Start is called in a goroutine and Stop is called simu
ltaneously. Actually looking more carefully, `Start` blocks until all consumers 
finish (which is when context is cancelled or stopCh is closed). This is fine.\n
\n2. In `bus.go`, the `Publish` method uses `b.pool.Go` which submits tasks to a
goroutine pool. The `ctx` is captured in the closure. This is generally fine but
if the context is cancelled, handlers may still run with a cancelled context. Th
e handler error is logged but the pool task continues. This is acceptable.\n\n3.
In `consumer.go`, `processPending` and `consumePartition` both read from the sam
e stream with the same consumerID. `processPending` uses "0" to read PEL message
s, then `consumePartition` uses ">" to read new messages. This is correct for Re
dis Stream consumer groups.\n\n4. In `consumer.go`, `handleMessage` does idempot
ency check, processes, marks processed, then ACKs. This ordering has a potential
issue: if the service crashes between processing and marking processed, the mess
age could be processed twice. But this is acceptable for at-least-once delivery.
\n\n5. In `consumer.go`, `retryOrDLQ` ACKs the message first, then requeues or s
ends to DLQ. This could lose messages if the requeue fails after ACK. This is a 
potential issue but not critical.\n\n6. In `event_dispatch_server.go`, the `disp
atch` method calls `e.publishEvent` in a goroutine pool. The `ctx` used is the s
erver context. This is fine.\n\n7. Architecture compliance:\n   - Biz layer (`in
ternal/biz/wapi/mixing.go`) uses `eventbus.StreamPublisher` and `eventbus.EventA
dapter` directly. This is a cross-layer concern. The eventbus package is in `int
ernal/pkg/eventbus` which is fine as a shared package.\n   - Data layer (`intern
al/data/wapi/data.go`) creates eventbus components. This is fine since data laye
r provides infrastructure.\n   - Server layer wraps consumer. Fine.\n   - Servic
e layer has `QuestSubscriber` which uses eventbus. Fine.\n   - The `EventDispatc
hServer` in `wcore` uses eventbus publisher. Fine.\n\n8. The `MixingUseCase` in 
biz layer directly depends on `eventbus.StreamPublisher` and `eventbus.EventAdap
ter`. This might be slightly concerning from a pure architecture perspective but
`internal/pkg` is designed for shared packages.\n\n9. Naming conventions seem fi
ne. Go camelCase is used.\n\n10. In `consumer.go` `ensureConsumerGroup`, error c
hecking uses string matching for "BUSYGROUP". This is fragile but common with Re
dis.\n\n11. In `idempotent.go`, `IsProcessed` uses `Get` which is fine. `MarkPro
cessed` uses `Set` with TTL. Good.\n\n12. `EventAdapter` methods all return erro
rs from proto.Marshal. Good error handling.\n\n13. The `MixingUseCase` event pub
lishing is best-effort (logs warning on failure). This is acceptable.\n\n14. The
`event_dispatch_server.go` has `publishEvent` that ignores `events.DestroyEventT
ype` when building `CombatKillEvent` - it passes `0, 0` for targetFishID and tar
getZoneID. Wait, let me look again:\n```go\ncase events.DestroyEventType:\n    i
f !event.Target.HasMaster() {\n        return\n    }\n    ev, buildErr = e.event
Adp.BuildCombatKillEvent(event.Target.MasterInfo().MasterId, event.Target.Id(), 
0, 0, time.Now().UnixMilli())\n```\nIt passes 0 for targetFishID and targetZoneI
D. That seems like a bug or incomplete implementation. The CombatKillEvent has K
illerFishId = event.Target.Id() but TargetFishId = 0. This looks suspicious but 
it might be intentional.\n\n15. In `bus.go`, `Publish` doesn\'t wait for handler
s to complete. It fires and forgets. This is by design.\n\n16. `EventConsumerSer
ver.Start` has panic recovery. Good.\n\n17. In `consumer.go`, the `consumePartit
ion` function doesn\'t handle the case where `consumerID` is empty consistently 
- it generates a new consumerID every time it\'s called (with `time.Now().UnixNa
no()`). This means each partition goroutine gets a different consumerID. Actuall
y wait, `consumePartition` is called once per partition in a loop. Each call gen
erates a new consumerID. This is fine because each partition is a separate strea
m.\n\n18. Wait, actually `consumePartition` generates `consumerID` inside the fu
nction, and `processPending` is called from `consumePartition` which uses the sa
me `consumerID`. That\'s fine.\n\n19. In `consumer.go`, `Start` creates `Partiti
on` number of goroutines. If `Partition` is large, this could be a lot. But 16 i
s the default, which is fine.\n\n20. In `consumer.go` `handleMessage`, when unma
rshal fails, it ACKs and drops the message. This could lead to data loss but pre
vents poison pills.\n\n21. In `publisher.go`, `streamKey` handles negative userI
Ds by taking absolute value. Good.\n\n22. The `Data` struct has `EventBus eventb
us.PubSub` - let me check what PubSub is.\n\nLet me read a few more files to und
erstand PubSub.',
