ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='The golangci-lint errors are mostly typecheck issues related to impor
t analysis problems in the linter itself (unsupported version: 2), not actual co
de issues. The only real issue is `internal/service/wapi/handler/on_auth.go:27:1
8: h.InnerAuth undefined` which seems to be a pre-existing issue unrelated to th
is PR.\n\nLet me verify that by checking if that file is in the PR diff list. Lo
oking at the diff files, `internal/service/wapi/handler/on_auth.go` is not in th
e list. So it\'s a pre-existing issue.\n\nLet me also check the `internal/biz/wa
pi/mixing_test.go` coverage since that\'s where the main new biz logic is.\n\nLe
t me now also check if there are any issues with the `EventDispatchServer` and `
EventConsumerServer` regarding goroutine leaks or panic recovery.\n\nKey observa
tions:\n1. `EventConsumerServer.Start` has panic recovery. Good.\n2. `EventDispa
tchServer.Start` spawns goroutines per zone but has no panic recovery. This is a
potential issue.\n3. `EventDispatchServer.Stop` just sets `started = false`. The
goroutines may not exit immediately because they\'re blocked on `zz.WhenEventCom
e`. This could lead to goroutine leaks on shutdown.\n4. In `event_dispatch_serve
r.go`, the `publishEvent` for `events.DestroyEventType` passes `0, 0` for `targe
tFishID` and `targetZoneID`. This looks like incomplete implementation.\n\nLet m
e check the `event_dispatch_server.go` more carefully. Actually the `DestroyEven
tType` maps to `CombatKillEvent` but with zeros for target - this is likely beca
use the target is already destroyed and doesn\'t have an ID. Still, it\'s worth 
noting.\n\nNow let me check the test coverage for `internal/biz/wapi` - it says 
70.0% which meets the threshold.\n\nLet me also check if there are any security 
issues:\n- No SQL injection (uses parameterized queries via ent)\n- No obvious b
uffer overflows\n- The Redis keys use prefixes, fine.\n\nArchitecture issues:\n-
`MixingUseCase` in biz layer directly depends on `eventbus.StreamPublisher` and 
`eventbus.EventAdapter`. This is acceptable since `internal/pkg` is a shared pac
kage.\n- `EventDispatchServer` in server layer uses eventbus. Fine.\n- `LoginHan
dler` in service layer uses eventbus. Fine.\n- Data layer creates eventbus compo
nents. Fine.\n\nWait, let me look at the `EventConsumerServer` more carefully. I
n `Start`:\n```go\ngo func() {\n    defer func() {\n        if r := recover(); r
!= nil {\n            log.Context(ctx).Errorw("event consumer panic recovered", 
"panic", r)\n        }\n    }()\n    if err := s.consumer.Start(ctx); err != nil
{\n        log.Context(ctx).Errorw("event consumer stopped with error", "error",
err)\n    }\n}()\n```\nThis is good - panic recovery around the consumer.\n\nIn 
`event_dispatch_server.go`:\n```go\ngo func(zz wcc.Zone) {\n    rd := rand.New(r
and.NewSource(time.Now().UnixNano()))\n    for e.started {\n        if err := zz
.WhenEventCome(ctx, func(event *wcc.RWEvent) error {\n            event.Complete
(e.dispatch(ctx, zz, event, e.wwsCli, rd))\n            return nil\n        }); 
err != nil {\n            log.Context(ctx).Warn(err)\n            continue\n    
   }\n    }\n}(z)\n```\nNo panic recovery here. If `e.dispatch` panics, it will 
crash the core service. However, `dispatch` itself doesn\'t seem to do anything 
that would panic easily. But `publishEvent` is called in a goroutine:\n```go\nif
e.publisher != nil {\n    e.innerEventPool.Go(func() {\n        e.publishEvent(c
tx, event)\n    })\n}\n```\nThe `innerEventPool` is a gopool which may or may no
t have panic recovery. By default, gopool does recover panics. Let me check - ac
tually `gopool` from bytedance does recover panics by default. So that\'s fine.\
n\nBut the outer `WhenEventCome` loop has no panic recovery. If `e.dispatch` pan
ics, the whole process crashes. This is a MEDIUM risk issue.\n\nActually wait - 
`e.dispatch` returns the error from `e.routers.Router(...)`. The router call its
elf could panic. Without panic recovery in the zone goroutine, this is a gap.\n\
nAlso, `EventDispatchServer.Stop` sets `e.started = false` but doesn\'t wait for
goroutines to finish. This is a goroutine leak on shutdown. However, the prompt 
says "goroutine泄露" is a check item. If it\'s just setting a flag and not waiti
ng, it\'s technically a leak but usually acceptable for short-lived shutdown.\n\
nLet me now check if there are any other issues with the PR.\n\nIn `consumer.go`
, `Start` method:\n```go\nfunc (c *redisStreamConsumer) Start(ctx context.Contex
t) error {\n    ...\n    for i := 0; i < c.config.Partition; i++ {\n        stre
amKey := fmt.Sprintf("%s:%d", c.config.StreamKeyPrefix, i)\n        if err := c.
ensureConsumerGroup(ctx, streamKey); err != nil {\n            return fmt.Errorf
("ensure consumer group failed for %s: %w", streamKey, err)\n        }\n        
c.wg.Add(1)\n        go c.consumePartition(ctx, streamKey)\n    }\n\n    c.wg.Wa
it()\n    return nil\n}\n```\nIf `ensureConsumerGroup` fails for partition N, it
returns an error but the previous N-1 goroutines are already running. The `wg.Wa
it()` is never reached. This means:\n1. Error is returned\n2. Previous goroutine
s keep running\n3. `Stop` may not be called\n\nThis is a goroutine leak in error
scenarios. The proper fix would be to ensure groups first, then start goroutines
. Or track started goroutines and stop them.\n\nActually, looking at it again: `
ensureConsumerGroup` is called inside the loop before `wg.Add(1)` and `go c.cons
umePartition`. If it fails on iteration 3, iterations 1 and 2 already started go
routines. The function returns without waiting. This is indeed a goroutine leak 
issue.\n\nLet me think about whether this is blocking or not. The PR introduces 
this consumer. If Redis has issues, some goroutines leak. This is a real issue b
ut might not be critical enough to block. I\'d classify it as a blocking issue b
ecause it violates the "无性能隐患（goroutine泄露、死锁等）" standard.\n\nWait, 
let me re-read the review criteria:\n- 无性能隐患（goroutine泄露、死锁等）\n\nAn
y of these unmet means NEEDS_FIX. But the question is whether this is a "serious
" goroutine leak. If `Start` returns an error, the application typically exits o
r restarts, so leaked goroutines would be cleaned up by process exit. In a long-
running process though, if this is retried, it could accumulate goroutines.\n\nA
ctually, `EventConsumerServer.Start` calls `s.consumer.Start(ctx)` in a goroutin
e. If it returns an error, the goroutine logs it and exits. The leaked consumer 
goroutines from `consumePartition` would still be running, waiting on Redis. The
y would exit when the parent context is cancelled (app shutdown) or when `stopCh
` is closed. Since the error path doesn\'t close `stopCh`, they wait on context 
cancellation. If the app\'s context is long-lived, they keep running.\n\nThis is
a MEDIUM severity issue.\n\nAlso, in `event_dispatch_server.go`, `publishEvent` 
for `DestroyEventType`:\n```go\nev, buildErr = e.eventAdp.BuildCombatKillEvent(e
vent.Target.MasterInfo().MasterId, event.Target.Id(), 0, 0, time.Now().UnixMilli
())\n```\nIt passes 0 for `targetFishID` and `targetZoneID`. Looking at the `Bui
ldCombatKillEvent` signature:\n```go\nfunc (a *EventAdapter) BuildCombatKillEven
t(killerUserID, killerFishID, targetFishID, targetZoneID, killAtMs int64) (*shar
edpb.Event, error)\n```\nSo for a destroy event, the `killerFishID` is set to `e
vent.Target.Id()` (the fish that died), but `targetFishID` is 0. This seems sema
ntically wrong - the target should be the one that was killed, not 0. This looks
like a bug. Actually, a "destroy" event might mean the fish was destroyed (kille
d) by the environment, so there\'s no killer. But then why set `killerFishID` to
the target\'s ID? This is confusing.\n\nActually wait, `events.DestroyEventType`
is probably when a fish dies. The `event.Target` is the fish that died. Setting 
`killerFishID = event.Target.Id()` and `targetFishID = 0` doesn\'t make sense. I
t should probably be:\n- `killerUserID = event.Target.MasterInfo().MasterId`  \n
- `killerFishID = 0` (no killer, or the killer is unknown)\n- `targetFishID = ev
ent.Target.Id()`\n- `targetZoneID = event.Target.ZoneId()`\n\nThis is definitely
a bug. I\'ll mark it as blocking.\n\nWait, let me check the actual usage. The `C
ombatKillEvent` is consumed by `QuestSubscriber` which just logs it for now (TOD
O). So it doesn\'t break anything currently. But it\'s still a bug in the event 
data.\n\nLet me now compile my findings.\n\nSummary:\n- Code style: Good, gofmt 
passes, naming is fine\n- Error handling: Good in most places\n- Architecture: C
ompliant\n- Test coverage: eventbus 79.4%, wapi 70.0%, wmix 74.2%, wcity/wcc 29.
7% (but wcity is just building map, not the main new feature)\n- Security: No SQ
L injection, no obvious issues\n- Performance/Safety:\n  - Goroutine leak in `re
disStreamConsumer.Start` error path\n  - Panic recovery missing in `EventDispatc
hServer` zone goroutines\n  - Bug in `event_dispatch_server.go` `DestroyEventTyp
e` event mapping\n\nWait, the `EventDispatchServer` goroutine leak on Stop: `Sto
p` sets `started = false` but doesn\'t wait. However, the goroutines are blocked
on `zz.WhenEventCome`. Without a way to interrupt that, there\'s no clean shutdo
wn. This is a design limitation, not necessarily a leak that causes problems at 
runtime. I\'ll note it as non-blocking.\n\nFor the `redisStreamConsumer.Start` g
oroutine leak: This is more concrete. If `ensureConsumerGroup` fails mid-way, st
arted goroutines leak.\n\nLet me check if there\'s a test for this. Looking at t
he tests, no.\n\nFor the `DestroyEventType` bug, this is in `internal/server/wco
re/wcc/event_dispatch_server.go` line 117:\n```go\nev, buildErr = e.eventAdp.Bui
ldCombatKillEvent(event.Target.MasterInfo().MasterId, event.Target.Id(), 0, 0, t
ime.Now().UnixMilli())\n```\n\nActually wait, I need to re-read. `event.Target` 
is the thing that was destroyed (killed). `event.Target.Id()` is the fish ID of 
the target. But it\'s passed as `killerFishID`. And `targetFishID` is 0. This is
