ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='Great! So the wmix coverage is now 74.2%, which meets the 70% thresho
ld. The wmix MixingUseCase.Mix method now also publishes MixEvent in the synchro
nous branch. The previous report\'s blocking issues have been fixed.\n\nNow I ne
ed to do my own independent review and find any remaining issues. Let me re-chec
k the issues I identified:\n\n1. **`redisStreamConsumer.Start` goroutine leak on
error** - If `ensureConsumerGroup` fails mid-loop, previously started goroutines
leak because `wg.Wait()` is never reached and `stopCh` is never closed. This is 
a real issue.\n\n2. **`EventDispatchServer` zone goroutines lack panic recovery*
* - If `e.dispatch` panics, the core service crashes. This is a real issue.\n\n3
. **`event_dispatch_server.go` `DestroyEventType` mapping bug** - `BuildCombatKi
llEvent` gets `event.Target.Id()` as `killerFishID` and `0` as `targetFishID`. T
his is semantically wrong. The `targetFishID` should be `event.Target.Id()` and 
`targetZoneID` should be `event.Target.ZoneId()`.\n\n4. **`EventDispatchServer.S
top` doesn\'t wait for goroutines** - Sets `started = false` but doesn\'t wait. 
However, the goroutines are blocked on channel reads from `WhenEventCome`. Witho
ut closing those channels, they can\'t exit. This is a design limitation. I\'ll 
note it but it\'s not a runtime leak that grows unbounded.\n\nLet me also check 
one more thing - does `EventConsumerServer.Start` actually have a goroutine leak
issue? No, because it wraps `consumer.Start` in a goroutine and the consumer its
elf manages its goroutines with `wg.Wait()`. The panic recovery is there too.\n\
nWait, actually there\'s another issue. In `EventConsumerServer.Start`:\n```go\n
func (s *EventConsumerServer) Start(ctx context.Context) error {\n    log.Contex
t(ctx).Info("starting event consumer server...")\n    if err := s.consumer.Ping(
ctx); err != nil {\n        return fmt.Errorf("event consumer ping failed: %w", 
err)\n    }\n    go func() {\n        defer func() {\n            if r := recove
r(); r != nil {\n                log.Context(ctx).Errorw("event consumer panic r
ecovered", "panic", r)\n            }\n        }()\n        if err := s.consumer
.Start(ctx); err != nil {\n            log.Context(ctx).Errorw("event consumer s
topped with error", "error", err)\n        }\n    }()\n    return nil\n}\n```\nT
his is fine.\n\nNow for the `redisStreamConsumer.Start` issue. Let me think abou
t severity. If `ensureConsumerGroup` fails on partition 3 of 16, partitions 1-2 
are running. The `Start` method returns an error. The caller (`EventConsumerServ
er.Start` goroutine) logs the error and exits. But partitions 1-2 are still runn
ing, consuming messages from Redis. They will only stop when:\n1. The applicatio
n context is cancelled (app shutdown)\n2. `stopCh` is closed (which requires `St
op` to be called)\n\nSince `Start` returned an error, `Stop` might never be call
ed. The goroutines will run until app shutdown. If the app has a restart loop th
at retries `Start`, each failed attempt leaks more goroutines. This is definitel
y a goroutine leak and a blocking issue.\n\nActually, I should check if kratos c
alls `Stop` when `Start` returns an error. Looking at kratos source, typically i
f a server `Start` returns an error, kratos will call `Stop` on all other server
s and then exit. But it won\'t call `Stop` on the server whose `Start` already r
eturned an error. So for `EventConsumerServer`, if `Start` returns an error befo
re starting the goroutine, then `Stop` is never called. But in our case, `EventC
onsumerServer.Start` starts a goroutine that calls `consumer.Start`, and `EventC
onsumerServer.Start` itself returns `nil`. So kratos thinks the server started s
uccessfully. Then the goroutine might later log an error from `consumer.Start`, 
but kratos doesn\'t know about it. So the leaked goroutines from `consumer.Start
`\'s `ensureConsumerGroup` failure will keep running.\n\nThis is a MEDIUM/HIGH s
everity issue.\n\nWait, actually `EventConsumerServer.Start` does:\n```go\ngo fu
nc() {\n    if err := s.consumer.Start(ctx); err != nil {\n        log.Context(c
tx).Errorw("event consumer stopped with error", "error", err)\n    }\n}()\n```\n
The goroutine logs the error. The goroutines leaked from `consumer.Start` (parti
tions 1-2) continue running. So we have a leak.\n\nHow to fix:\n```go\nfunc (c *
redisStreamConsumer) Start(ctx context.Context) error {\n    // First ensure all
consumer groups\n    streamKeys := make([]string, c.config.Partition)\n    for i
:= 0; i < c.config.Partition; i++ {\n        streamKey := fmt.Sprintf("%s:%d", c
.config.StreamKeyPrefix, i)\n        if err := c.ensureConsumerGroup(ctx, stream
Key); err != nil {\n            return fmt.Errorf("ensure consumer group failed 
for %s: %w", streamKey, err)\n        }\n        streamKeys[i] = streamKey\n    
}\n    \n    // Then start consumers\n    for _, streamKey := range streamKeys {
\n        c.wg.Add(1)\n        go c.consumePartition(ctx, streamKey)\n    }\n   
\n    c.wg.Wait()\n    return nil\n}\n```\nThis way, if any `ensureConsumerGroup
` fails, no goroutines are started.\n\nThis is a clear bug with a clear fix. I\'
ll mark it as blocking.\n\nFor the `EventDispatchServer` panic recovery issue:\n
```go\ngo func(zz wcc.Zone) {\n    rd := rand.New(rand.NewSource(time.Now().Unix
Nano()))\n    for e.started {\n        if err := zz.WhenEventCome(ctx, func(even
t *wcc.RWEvent) error {\n            event.Complete(e.dispatch(ctx, zz, event, e
.wwsCli, rd))\n            return nil\n        }); err != nil {\n            log
.Context(ctx).Warn(err)\n            continue\n        }\n    }\n}(z)\n```\nNo d
efer recover. If `e.dispatch` panics, the app crashes. The fix is simple:\n```go
\ngo func(zz wcc.Zone) {\n    defer func() {\n        if r := recover(); r != ni
l {\n            log.Context(ctx).Errorw("event dispatch panic recovered", "pani
c", r)\n        }\n    }()\n    rd := rand.New(rand.NewSource(time.Now().UnixNan
o()))\n    for e.started {\n        ...\n    }\n}(z)\n```\nBut wait, if it panic
s, the goroutine exits and no more events are processed for that zone. That\'s b
etter than crashing the whole service. This is also blocking because it violates
"panic 恢复" requirement.\n\nFor the `DestroyEventType` bug:\n```go\ncase events
.DestroyEventType:\n    if !event.Target.HasMaster() {\n        return\n    }\n 
  ev, buildErr = e.eventAdp.BuildCombatKillEvent(event.Target.MasterInfo().Maste
rId, event.Target.Id(), 0, 0, time.Now().UnixMilli())\n```\nThe fix should be:\n
```go\nev, buildErr = e.eventAdp.BuildCombatKillEvent(event.Target.MasterInfo().
MasterId, 0, event.Target.Id(), event.Target.ZoneId(), time.Now().UnixMilli())\n
```\nOr maybe there\'s no killer fish, so killerFishID should be 0. This is bloc
king because it\'s incorrect event data.\n\nWait, I should verify what `CombatKi
llEvent` fields mean. Looking at adapter.go:\n```go\nfunc (a *EventAdapter) Buil
dCombatKillEvent(killerUserID, killerFishID, targetFishID, targetZoneID, killAtM
s int64) (*sharedpb.Event, error) {\n    payload := &sharedpb.CombatKillEvent{\n
       KillerUserId: killerUserID,\n        KillerFishId: killerFishID,\n       
TargetFishId: targetFishID,\n        TargetZoneId: targetZoneID,\n        KillAt
Ms:     killAtMs,\n    }\n```\nSo for a destroy event where a fish dies (is dest
royed), the `target` is the fish that died. There is no `killer` in a destroy ev
ent (it\'s destruction, not combat kill). So:\n- `killerUserId` should probably 
be `event.Target.MasterInfo().MasterId` (the owner of the destroyed fish) or 0\n
- `killerFishId` should be 0 (no killer)\n- `targetFishId` should be `event.Targ
et.Id()` (the destroyed fish)\n- `targetZoneId` should be `event.Target.ZoneId()
`\n\nActually, looking at the event naming, `CombatKillEvent` implies someone ki
lled someone. But `DestroyEventType` is a fish being destroyed. Maybe they want 
to treat destruction as self-kill or environment kill. Either way, setting `targ
etFishId = 0` loses the identity of the destroyed fish, which makes the event us
eless for quest tracking. This is a bug.\n\nLet me also check the `EarnEventType
`:\n```go\ncase events.EarnEventType:\n    if !event.Target.HasMaster() {\n     
  return\n    }\n    amount := int64(0)\n    if event.Body != nil {\n        if 
a, ok := event.Body[events.FieldAmount].(int64); ok {\n            amount = a\n 
      }\n    }\n    ev, buildErr = e.eventAdp.BuildCombatEarnEvent(event.Target.
MasterInfo().MasterId, event.Target.Id(), event.Target.ZoneId(), amount, time.No
w().UnixMilli())\n```\nThis one looks correct - `event.Target` is the fish that 
earned.\n\nFor `SleepEventType`:\n```go\ncase events.SleepEventType:\n    if !ev
ent.Source.HasMaster() {\n        return\n    }\n    ev, buildErr = e.eventAdp.B
uildFishSleepEvent(event.Source.MasterInfo().MasterId, event.Source.Id(), event.
Source.ZoneId(), time.Now().UnixMilli(), 0)\n```\nThis uses `event.Source` inste
ad of `event.Target`. That makes sense - sleep events might have the fish as the
source. This looks fine.\n\nSo the `DestroyEventType` bug is real.\n\nNow, test 
coverage:\n- `internal/pkg/eventbus`: 79.4% ✅\n- `internal/biz/wapi`: 70.0% ✅\
n- `internal/biz/wmix`: 74.2% ✅\n- `internal/biz/wcity/wcc`: 29.7% ❌ - but thi
s is for `building_map.go` which has event bus integration. The overall `wcity` 
has no test files for the main package. But the requirement says "Biz 层测试覆盖
率 ≥ 70%". Does this apply to ALL biz packages or just the ones modified? The pr
ompt says "Biz 层测试覆盖率 ≥ 70%". Looking at the test run:\n  - `new-world/int
ernal/biz/wcity\t[no test files]` - 0% coverage\n  - `new-world/internal/biz/wci
ty/wcc\t(cached)\tcoverage: 29.7% of statements`\n  \n  The `wcc` package covera
ge is 29.7%. But the main changes in this PR for event bus are in `wapi`, `wmix`
