ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='The golangci-lint errors are mostly typecheck issues related to impor
t analysis problems in the linter itself (unsupported version: 2), not actual co
de issues. The only real issue is `internal/service/wapi/handler/on_auth.go:27:1
8: h.InnerAuth undefined` which seems to be a pre-existing issue unrelated to th
is PR.\n\nLet me verify that by checking if that file is in the PR diff list. Lo
oking at the diff files, `internal/service/wapi/handler/on_auth.go` is not in th
e list. So it\'s a pre-existing issue.\n\nLet me also check the `internal/biz/wa
pi/mixing_test.go` coverage since that\'s where the main new biz logic is.\n\nLe
t me now also check if there are any issues with the `EventDispatchServer` and `
EventConsumerServer` regarding goroutine leaks or panic recovery.\n\nKey observa
tions:\n1. `EventConsumerServer.Start` has panic recovery. Good.\n2. `EventDispa
tchServer.Start` spawns goroutines per zone but has no panic recovery. This is a
potential issue.\n3. `EventDispatchServer.Stop` just sets `started = false`. The
goroutines may not exit immediately because they\'re blocked on `zz.WhenEventCom
e`. This could lead to goroutine leaks on shutdown.\n4. In `event_dispatch_serve
r.go`, the `publishEvent` for `events.DestroyEventType` passes `0, 0` for `targe
tFishID` and `targetZoneID`. This looks like incomplete implementation.\n\nLet m
e check the `event_dispatch_server.go` more carefully. Actually the `DestroyEven
tType` maps to `CombatKillEvent` but with zeros for target - this is likely beca
use the target is already destroyed and doesn\'t have an ID. Still, it\'s worth 
noting.\n\nNow let me check the test coverage for `internal/biz/wapi` - it says 
70.0% which meets the threshold.\n\nLet me also check if there are any security 
issues:\n- No SQL injection (uses parameterized queries via ent)\n- No obvious b
uffer overflows\n- The Redis keys use prefixes, fine.\n\nArchitecture issues:\n-
`MixingUseCase` in biz layer directly depends on `eventbus.StreamPublisher` and 
`eventbus.EventAdapter`. This is acceptable since `internal/pkg` is a shared pac
kage.\n- `EventDispatchServer` in server layer uses eventbus. Fine.\n- `LoginHan
dler` in service layer uses eventbus. Fine.\n- Data layer creates eventbus compo
nents. Fine.\n\nWait, let me look at the `EventConsumerServer` more carefully. I
n `Start`:\n```go\ngo func() {\n    defer func() {\n        if r := recover(); r
!= nil {\n            log.Context(ctx).Errorw("event consumer panic recovered", 
"panic", r)\n        }\n    }()\n    if err := s.consumer.Start(ctx); err != nil
{\n        log.Context(ctx).Errorw("event consumer stopped with error", "error",
err)\n    }\n}()\n```\nThis is good - panic recovery around the consumer.\n\nIn 
`event_dispatch_server.go`:\n```go\ngo func(zz wcc.Zone) {\n    rd := rand.New(r
and.NewSource(time.Now().UnixNano()))\n    for e.started {\n        if err := zz
.WhenEventCome(ctx, func(event *wcc.RWEvent) error {\n            event.Complete
(e.dispatch(ctx, zz, event, e.wwsCli, rd))\n            return nil\n        }); 
err != nil {\n            log.Context(ctx).Warn(err)\n            continue\n    
   }\n    }\n}(z)\n```\nNo panic recovery here. If `e.dispatch` panics, it will 
crash the core service. However, `dispatch` itself doesn\'t seem to do anything 
that would panic easily. But `publishEvent` is called in a goroutine:\n```go\nif
e.publisher != nil {\n    e.innerEventPool.Go(func() {\n        e.publishEvent(c
tx, event)\n    })\n}\n```\nThe `innerEventPool` is a gopool which may or may no
t have panic recovery. By default, gopool does recover panics. Let me check - ac
tually `gopool` from bytedance does recover panics by default. So that\'s fine.\
n\nBut the outer `WhenEventCome` loop has no panic recovery. If `e.dispatch` pan
ics, the whole process crashes. This is a MEDIUM risk issue.\n\nActually wait - 
`e.dispatch` returns the error from `e.routers.Router(...)`. The router call its
elf could panic. Without panic recovery in the zone goroutine, this is a gap.\n\
nAlso, `EventDispatchServer.Stop` sets `e.started = false` but doesn\'t wait for
goroutines to finish. This is a goroutine leak on shutdown. However, the prompt 
says "goroutine泄露" is a check item. If it\'s just setting a flag and not waiti
ng, it\'s technically a leak but usually acceptable for short-lived shutdown.\n\
nLet me now check if there are any other issues with the PR.\n\nIn `consumer.go`
